Preheat your oven to 200°C. Pop the @diced butternut squash{300%g} on a #baking tray{} with a little @olive oil{}. Sprinkle over half the @mild curry powder{1} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Use your hands to coat the squash in the spices. Roast on the top shelf of your oven until soft and golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through to ensure even cooking.

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(peeled and thinly sliced). Halve the @red chilli{1/2} lengthways, deseed then finely chop. Chop the @medium tomato{2} into 2cm chunks. Roughly chop the @coriander{1}(roughly chopped, stalks and all).

Heat a splash of @oil{} in a large #saucepan{} on medium heat, add the curry powder, tomato and as much chilli as you dare. Cook for ~{1%minute}. Add the @water{400%ml}, @vegetable stock powder{1}, @coconut milk{200%ml} and @red split lentils{200%g} to the saucepan. Simmer until the lentils are soft, ~{20-25%minutes}. Stir every couple of minutes to check the lentils don't catch on the bottom of the pan.

Separate the onion slices. Toss them in the @plain flour{8}(tossed in) and season with a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Heat a splash of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on high heat. When hot, fry the onion until coloured and crispy, ~{2-3%minutes}. Turn once or twice, then transfer to some #kitchen paper{} to absorb any excess oil.

Meanwhile, pop the @plain naans{2} into the oven to warm through for ~{2-3%minutes}.

Once the coconut dal has thickened and the lentils are cooked, taste for seasoning and add salt and black pepper if needed. Stir in half the coriander. Serve in big #bowls{} with the roasted butternut squash, crispy onions and @pumpkin seeds{15} stacked on top. Sprinkle over the remaining coriander and mop up with your naans. Enjoy!